1 Background

As a statistical consultant working for a real estate investment firm, your task is to develop a model to predict the selling price of a given home in Ames, Iowa. Your employer hopes to use this information to help assess whether the asking price of a house is higher or lower than the true value of the house. If the home is undervalued, it may be a good investment for the firm.

2 Training Data and relevant packages

In order to better assess the quality of the model you will produce, the data have been randomly divided into three separate pieces: a training data set, a testing data set, and a validation data set. For now we will load the training data set, the others will be loaded and used later.

2.2 Part 2 - Development and assessment of an initial model, following a semi-guided process of analysis

2.2.1 Section 2.1 An Initial Model

In building a model, it is often useful to start by creating a simple, intuitive initial model based on the results of the exploratory data analysis. (Note: The goal at this stage is not to identify the best possible model but rather to choose a reasonable and understandable starting point. Later you will expand and revise this model to create your final model.

Based on your EDA, select at most 10 predictor variables from ames_train and create a linear model for price (or a transformed version of price) using those variables. Provide the R code and the summary output table for your model, a brief justification for the variables you have chosen, and a brief discussion of the model results in context (focused on the variables that appear to be important predictors and how they relate to sales price).

2.2.1.1

Ive decided to use area, SqFt, baths, Garage.Area, Total.Bsmt.SF, and Central.Air for the initial model. These variables were chosen based on their strong relationships to price shown in the exploratory data analysis. The summary table for the model shown below shows that most of these variables have a strong to very strong relationship to price (based on the Pr(>|t|)). The one surprise is the variable areas (lot area) relationship to price. It has a relatively high Pr(>|t|) and has a negative relationship to price. The models predictive power appears to be strong based on Adjusted R-squared (0.7203) and p-value: < 2.2e-16.

# remove outliers in terms of number of baths identified in the exploratory analysis
ames_train_filtered <- data1 %>% filter(baths > 0.5) %>% filter(baths < 5)

ames_train_filtered <- stats::na.omit(ames_train_filtered)

model.full <- lm(price ~ area + SqFt + baths + Garage.Area + Total.Bsmt.SF + Central.Air,
                 data = ames_train_filtered)

summary(model.full)

2.2.3 Section 2.3 Initial Model Residuals

One way to assess the performance of a model is to examine the models residuals. In the space below, create a residual plot for your preferred model from above and use it to assess whether your model appears to fit the data well. Comment on any interesting structure in the residual plot (trend, outliers, etc.) and briefly discuss potential implications it may have for your model and inference / prediction you might produce.

2.2.3.1

We see from the residuals plot below that the model performs reasonably well up to about $300k. As prices rise above $300k the predictions are increasingly too low. Houses in this range make up the bulk of the dataset (970 or 97.5%), so we are likely going to gain value by being able to predict prices in this range.

pred.test.MPM <- predict(model.BIC, ames_train_filtered, 
                    estimator="MPM", 
                    prediction=TRUE, se.fit=TRUE)

resid.MPM = ames_train_filtered$price - pred.test.MPM$fit

ames_train_filtered1 <- ames_train_filtered %>% mutate(pred.test.MPM$fit) 

colnames(ames_train_filtered1)[14] <- "fit"

ames_train_filtered1 <- ames_train_filtered1 %>% dplyr::select(price, fit)

plot(ames_train_filtered$price, resid.MPM, 
     xlab="Price",
     ylab="Residuals")

nrow(ames_train_filtered %>% filter(price < 400000))
## [1] 968

2.2.5 Section 2.5 Overfitting

The process of building a model generally involves starting with an initial model (as you have done above), identifying its shortcomings, and adapting the model accordingly. This process may be repeated several times until the model fits the data reasonably well. However, the model may do well on training data but perform poorly out-of-sample (meaning, on a dataset other than the original training data) because the model is overly-tuned to specifically fit the training data. This is called overfitting. To determine whether overfitting is occurring on a model, compare the performance of a model on both in-sample and out-of-sample data sets. To look at performance of your initial model on out-of-sample data, you will use the data set ames_test.

load("ames_test.Rdata")

Use your model from above to generate predictions for the housing prices in the test data set. Are the predictions significantly more accurate (compared to the actual sales prices) for the training data than the test data? Why or why not? Briefly explain how you determined that (what steps or processes did you use)?

Below I used the residuals plot and the RMSE to evaluate the performance of the model on the test set. As compared to the performance on the training set, the residuals plot shows that the model performs worse on the test data at higher prices. As stated previously, the model performs well at prices below $400k, which is the vast mahjority of the data (97.5%). With regard to RMSE, the model performs much better on the test data (RMSE = 35461.43) as compared to the training data (RMSE = 43047.46). This confirms that the model can perform very well on the vast majority of new houses (price < $400k).

ames_test_filtered <- ames_test %>% 
  mutate(SqFt = X1st.Flr.SF + X2nd.Flr.SF) %>% 
  mutate(baths = Full.Bath + 0.5*Half.Bath) %>% 
  dplyr::select(price, Overall.Qual, Garage.Area, Total.Bsmt.SF, Garage.Cars, area, baths, 
                Bedroom.AbvGr, Year.Built, SqFt, Lot.Area, Central.Air, Overall.Cond) %>% 
  filter(baths > 0.5) %>% filter(baths < 5)

pred.test.MPM <- predict(model.BIC, ames_test_filtered, 
                    estimator="MPM", 
                    prediction=TRUE, se.fit=TRUE)

resid.MPM = ames_test_filtered$price - pred.test.MPM$fit

ames_test_filtered1 <- ames_test_filtered %>% mutate(pred.test.MPM$fit) 

colnames(ames_test_filtered1)[14] <- "fit"

ames_test_filtered1 <- ames_test_filtered1 %>% dplyr::select(price, fit)

plot(ames_test_filtered$price, resid.MPM, 
     xlab="Price",
     ylab="Residuals")

pred.MPM.rmse <- sqrt(mean((pred.test.MPM$fit - ames_test_filtered$price)^2))
pred.MPM.rmse
## [1] 35461.43

Note to the learner: If in real-life practice this out-of-sample analysis shows evidence that the training data fits your model a lot better than the test data, it is probably a good idea to go back and revise the model (usually by simplifying the model) to reduce this overfitting. For simplicity, we do not ask you to do this on the assignment, however.

2.3.1.2

We see that the model.AICf has the higher R^2 (0.9122), so well proceed with that one. This compares very favorably to the model in the previous section, which had a R^2 of 0.7203. The model.AICf removed the variable SqFt. The model model.BICf removed SqFt, baths, and Garage.Cars.

The The RMSE of 42755.65 is comparable to that found from the smaller model in the previous section (43047.46).

The residuals plot shows that the model works very well (random scatter around 0) upto $500k, which is better than the model in the previous section. There is one extreme outlier of with a residual of -554,810.

We saw from ggpairs that area and SqFt were strongly correlated (0.996), so both are not needed. The stepAIC cosnequently removed SqFt in the final model.

2.3.2 Section 3.2 Transformation

Did you decide to transform any variables? Why or why not? Explain in a few sentences.

2.3.2.1

No.None of the variables had a nonlinear relationship to price.

2.3.3 Section 3.3 Variable Interaction

Did you decide to include any variable interactions? Why or why not? Explain in a few sentences.

The SqFt variable was removed from the model. It was strongly correlated with the area variable. When 2 variables are strongly correlated, including both does not provide any more predictive power than including only one of the variables.

2.3.4 Section 3.4 Variable Selection

What method did you use to select the variables you included? Why did you select the method you used? Explain in a few sentences.

I used stepwise selection, which is a combination of backward and forward selection. It iteratively adds and removes variables in order to find the best performing model. I tried both AIC and BIC. AIC had a higher R^2, so we selected that model.
